  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key features often include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. In the United States, key laws include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n\n3. International standards are set by:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n\n4. Regulations typically cover:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n\n5. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Large fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of operating licenses\n\nMost developed countries have comprehensive AML regulations to prevent financial crimes and terrorist financing.",
